
Day Planner CLI
Product Requirements Document
Version 0.1  —  March 2026  —  Draft
Author
Ewan Greer
Status
Draft
Last Updated
March 2026
Version
0.1



1. Overview
Day Planner CLI is a locally-run, terminal-based planning tool designed to help a solo developer take back control of their workday. It aggregates tasks from existing tools (Taskwarrior, Jira) and guides the user through a structured daily ritual: commit to priorities in the morning, check in during the day, and review performance at close of day.
The tool is owned and operated by the individual. It is not tied to any company infrastructure. Integrations with employer-specific tools (e.g. Jira) are treated as optional, configurable plugins so the core tool remains portable across jobs.

2. Problem Statement
The target user (a software developer working in a team environment) has access to task management tools — Jira for project work, Taskwarrior for personal task tracking — but consistently fails to use them as a guide for the day. Instead, the day is shaped by reactive channels: Slack messages and emails pull attention in real time, and tasks with social urgency (e.g. PR review requests) displace planned work.

The root causes are:
Reactive channels (Slack, email) have immediate social pull; task tools are passive and easy to ignore.
There is no enforced start-of-day ritual to establish intent before the first distraction arrives.
Existing tools lack a feedback loop or scoring mechanism to make adherence feel rewarding.
No previous tool has been sticky enough to build a lasting habit.

3. Goals
3.1 In Scope
Provide a structured morning planning ritual that surfaces prioritised tasks and asks the user to commit to 2–3 goals for the day.
Send periodic nudges throughout the day to keep the user anchored to their commitments.
Allow lightweight check-ins to mark tasks complete or log progress.
Produce an end-of-day score and summary based on completion against commitments.
Implement a streak system to build a daily habit over time.
Integrate with Taskwarrior as the primary, always-available task source.
Support optional integration with Jira for work-specific tasks.
Run entirely locally; no cloud account or subscription required.

3.2 Out of Scope (v1)
Native Slack or email integration (policy and portability concerns).
Mobile or web interface (terminal-first; UI layer abstracted for future extension).
Team or multi-user features.
Calendar integration.
AI-powered sentiment analysis (planned for a later milestone).

4. User Persona
Name
Ewan
Role
Software Developer (solo contributor)
Environment
Terminal-comfortable; uses Taskwarrior, Jira, Slack, email daily
Core pain
Reactive to Slack/email; planned work gets displaced
Motivation
Wants to feel in control of the day and see measurable progress
Key constraint
Tool must be portable between employers; cannot rely on company infrastructure



5. Feature Requirements
5.1 Morning Planning (MVP)
Triggered by running the tool at the start of the day. The session should take no more than 2–3 minutes.

ID
Requirement
Priority
M-01
Pull pending tasks from Taskwarrior, sorted by urgency/priority
Must Have
M-02
Optionally pull open Jira issues assigned to the user (configurable)
Should Have
M-03
Present a ranked list and prompt the user to select 2–3 commitments for the day
Must Have
M-04
Persist the day’s commitments to a local data store
Must Have
M-05
Display current streak and yesterday’s score on launch
Should Have


5.2 Intraday Check-ins & Nudges
The tool runs a background process that nudges the user at configurable intervals and accepts lightweight status updates via a CLI command.

ID
Requirement
Priority
I-01
Background process sends a terminal notification at configurable intervals (default: every 90 minutes)
Must Have
I-02
Nudge displays the user’s current commitments as a reminder
Must Have
I-03
CLI command to mark a commitment as complete
Must Have
I-04
CLI command to log a brief progress note against a commitment
Should Have
I-05
Nudges are suppressed during user-defined focus/do-not-disturb windows
Could Have


