6. High-Level Architecture
The tool is designed with a clean separation of concerns to support the portability goal and make future UI changes straightforward.

Layer
Responsibility
Core / Domain
Day planning logic, scoring, streaks, data persistence. No UI or integration dependencies.
Integrations
Taskwarrior adapter, Jira adapter. Pluggable; new integrations added without touching core.
View Layer
Terminal UI (TUI) for v1. Abstracted behind an interface so it can be swapped for a web UI or desktop app later.
Background Service
Daemon or cron job responsible for delivering intraday nudges.
Data Store
Local flat files or SQLite database. Stores daily plans, completion records, streaks, and reflections.



7. Success Metrics
Since this is a personal tool, success is measured by subjective value and habit formation rather than business KPIs.
The user opens the tool at the start of the day on ≥5 consecutive working days within the first two weeks.
The user reports feeling more in control of their priorities compared to before.
Average daily completion score is ≥60% after the first month of consistent use.
A streak of ≥10 working days is achieved within the first 6 weeks.


8. Suggested Milestones
Milestone
Scope
Goal
M1 — Spike
Morning planning with Taskwarrior only. CLI input/output. Persist commitments to a file.
Validate the core loop works end-to-end
M2 — Core Loop
Add intraday nudges, check-in commands, and end-of-day scoring.
Tool is usable for a full working day
M3 — Habit Layer
Streaks, historical records, Jira integration.
Hook deepens; tool survives first few weeks
M4 — AI Layer
Sentiment analysis on daily reflections; pattern insights.
Tool becomes smarter over time



9. Open Questions
What language/runtime will the tool be built in? (Not yet decided — problem-driven, stack TBD.)
How should nudges be delivered on different OS environments? (terminal-notifier on macOS, notify-send on Linux, etc.)
What is the minimum viable scoring threshold to count a day as a “good” day for streak purposes?
Should the background nudge process be a persistent daemon or a simpler cron/launchd/systemd job?
What AI model/API will be used for sentiment analysis in a later milestone, and how does this fit the “run locally” ethos?
